.TH AUTOCUTSEL 1 "March 2026" "autocutsel @PACKAGE_VERSION@" "General Commands Manual"
.SH NAME
autocutsel \- keep the X clipboard and the cutbuffer in sync
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B autocutsel
.RB [ \-selection
.IR selection_name ]
.RB [ \-cutbuffer
.IR number ]
.RB [ \-debug ]
.RB [ \-verbose ]
.RB [ \-fork ]
.RB [ \-pause
.IR milliseconds ]
.RB [ \-buttonup ]
.RB [ \-mouseonly ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B autocutsel
tracks changes in the server's cutbuffer and clipboard selection. When the
clipboard is changed, it updates the cutbuffer. When the cutbuffer is changed,
it owns the clipboard selection. The cutbuffer and clipboard selection are
always synchronized.
.PP
This is useful for VNC sessions where Windows VNC clients synchronize the
Windows clipboard with the cutbuffer but not with the selections.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BR \-selection ", " \-select ", " \-sel ", " \-s " " \fIname\fR
Specify which selection to use. Default is CLIPBOARD.
.TP
.BR \-cutbuffer ", " \-cut ", " \-c " " \fInumber\fR
Specify which cutbuffer to use. Default is 0.
.TP
.BR \-debug ", " \-d
Print debugging information.
.TP
.BR \-verbose ", " \-v
Be more verbose. Reports the version and announces synchronizations.
.TP
.BR \-fork ", " \-f
Run as a daemon in the background.
.TP
.BR \-pause ", " \-p " " \fImilliseconds\fR
Set the polling interval in milliseconds. Default is 500.
.TP
.B \-buttonup
Only read the selection when mouse button 1 is not pressed. This may help
with applications like OpenOffice Writer that have trouble when the selection
is requested before the mouse button is released.
.TP
.B \-mouseonly
Synchronize PRIMARY to CLIPBOARD only when text is selected with the mouse.
Keyboard-based selections (e.g. Shift+Arrow) are ignored. This prevents
accidental clipboard overwrites in editors like VSCode where keyboard
selection would otherwise replace the clipboard content.
.PP
Only a single instance is needed \(em unlike the traditional setup which
requires two instances (one for CLIPBOARD, one for PRIMARY), the
.B \-mouseonly
option handles both selections in a single process. Typical usage:
.PP
.RS
autocutsel \-selection PRIMARY \-mouseonly
.RE
.PP
This option uses libinput to detect mouse button releases and works on both
X11 and Wayland (via XWayland). It requires libinput and libudev.
.PP
.B Note:
The
.B \-mouseonly
option requires read access to input devices
.RI ( /dev/input/* ).
The user running autocutsel must be a member of the
.B input
group:
.PP
.RS
sudo usermod \-aG input $USER
.RE
.PP
A re-login is required for the group change to take effect.
.SH EXAMPLES
Synchronize the CLIPBOARD selection with the cutbuffer (default):
.PP
.RS
autocutsel
.RE
.PP
Synchronize the PRIMARY selection with the cutbuffer:
.PP
.RS
autocutsel \-selection PRIMARY
.RE
.PP
Sync PRIMARY to CLIPBOARD on mouse selection only (single instance):
.PP
.RS
autocutsel \-selection PRIMARY \-mouseonly
.RE
.SH INSTANCE MANAGEMENT
.B autocutsel
automatically prevents multiple instances for the same selection. If an
instance monitoring the same selection is already running, additional
invocations will print a message to stderr and exit. This makes it safe to
place
.B autocutsel
in
.I .bashrc
or
.I .xinitrc
without spawning duplicate processes.
.PP
Different selections can still be monitored concurrently (e.g. one instance
for CLIPBOARD and one for PRIMARY).
.SH SYSTEMD
.B autocutsel
can be run as a systemd user service. A template unit
.RB ( autocutsel@.service )
and example configuration files are provided in
.IR contrib/systemd/ .
Each instance reads its options from
.IR ~/.config/autocutsel/<instance>.args .
.PP
.B Install the service:
.PP
If installed from an RPM package, the service file is already at
.IR /usr/lib/systemd/user/autocutsel@.service .
Just create the configuration:
.PP
.RS
.nf
mkdir \-p ~/.config/autocutsel
cp /usr/share/doc/autocutsel/examples/mouseonly.args ~/.config/autocutsel/
.fi
.RE
.PP
For manual installation:
.PP
.RS
.nf
mkdir \-p ~/.config/autocutsel ~/.config/systemd/user
cp contrib/systemd/autocutsel@.service ~/.config/systemd/user/
cp contrib/systemd/mouseonly.args ~/.config/autocutsel/
.fi
.RE
.PP
.B Available example configurations:
.TP
.I mouseonly.args
Sync PRIMARY to CLIPBOARD on mouse selection only (recommended, single instance).
.TP
.I clipboard.args
Sync CLIPBOARD with the cutbuffer (traditional setup, use together with primary.args).
.TP
.I primary.args
Sync PRIMARY with the cutbuffer (traditional setup, use together with clipboard.args).
.PP
Enable a single mouseonly instance (recommended):
.PP
.RS
.nf
systemctl \-\-user daemon\-reload
systemctl \-\-user enable \-\-now autocutsel@mouseonly
.fi
.RE
.PP
Or enable the traditional two\-instance setup:
.PP
.RS
.nf
systemctl \-\-user daemon\-reload
systemctl \-\-user enable \-\-now autocutsel@clipboard autocutsel@primary
.fi
.RE
.PP
View logs with:
.B journalctl \-\-user \-u 'autocutsel@*'
.PP
The service file includes systemd hardening options (sandboxing via
.BR PrivateUsers ,
.BR ProtectHome ,
.BR ProtectSystem ,
.BR NoNewPrivileges ,
etc.). The service uses
.B ConditionEnvironment=DISPLAY
to only start when an X11 display is available.
.PP
.B Compatibility:
The systemd service works on GNOME (since 3.34) and KDE Plasma (since 5.25)
on both X11 and Wayland. XFCE and standalone window managers do not activate
.B graphical\-session.target
by default and require manual setup.
.SH AUTHORS
Originally written by Michael Witrant <mike@lepton.fr>.
.br
Original repository: https://github.com/sigmike/autocutsel
.PP
